      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Is Fe³⁺ Consistently More Stable?\n\n**The short answer: Yes, for the overwhelming majority of ligands — but with important exceptions.**\n\n| Ligand Class | Typical Donor Atoms | Fe³⁺ vs Fe²⁺ | Reason |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Aminopolycarboxylates (EDTA, NTA, DTPA) | O, N | Fe³⁺ ≫ Fe²⁺ (Δlog β ≈ 10–15) | Fe³⁺ is a harder Lewis acid |\n| Hydroxamates, catecholates, phenolates | O | Fe³⁺ ≫ Fe²⁺ | Strong preference for hard O-donors |\n| Simple carboxylates (acetate, oxalate) | O | Fe³⁺ > Fe²⁺ | Hard-hard interaction dominates |\n| Polypyridyls (bipy, phen) | N (π-acceptor) | Fe²⁺ ≥ Fe³⁺ | Fe²⁺ (d⁶) benefits from back-bonding |\n| Thioethers, soft S-donors | S | Fe²⁺ ≥ Fe³⁺ | Soft ligands prefer softer metal |\n\n**Key chemistry insight:** Fe³⁺ (d⁵, high-spin, charge +3) is a **hard Lewis acid** and binds strongly to hard O- and N-donors. For EDTA alone, log β(Fe³⁺) ≈ 25.1 vs log β(Fe²⁺) ≈ 14.3 — a difference of ~11 log units, meaning Fe³⁺ binds ~10¹¹ times more strongly. This pattern holds broadly across the SRD-46 dataset for oxygen-donor ligands.\n\nThe exceptions arise with **π-accepting nitrogen donors** (1,10-phenanthroline, 2,2′-bipyridine), where Fe²⁺ (d⁶, low-spin in these complexes) gains extra stabilization through metal-to-ligand π back-bonding that Fe³⁺ cannot provide to the same extent.",
